  "text": "A sketch of the spectral domain PS-OCT system used for imaging the murine anterior segment is shown in Fig. 1 . Detailed specifications of the system can be found elsewhere, [CITATION_1] hence only a brief description is provided here. A polarization-maintaining (PM) fiber-based Michelson interferometer was illuminated by a superluminescent diode with a central wavelength of 837 nm and a full-width-at-half-maximum bandwidth of 52 nm. The incident light was linearly polarized, launched into the slow axis channel of the PM fiber system, and split into sample and reference arms. A quarter wave plate (QWP, at 45 deg) then provided circularly polarized light for sample illumination. After passing a pair of galvanometer scanners, a 4:5 telescope relayed the pivot point of the fast scanning mirror into the back focal plane of the 10× objective lens (Olympus E A10). The setup provided a transverse resolution of ∼10 μm in the focal plane and an axial resolution of 7.6 μm in air. The reference arm featured another QWP (at 22.5 deg) and glass blocks for dispersion balancing. The interfered light from sample and reference arm was split into two orthogonal components by a polarizing beam splitter. Each polarization component was then detected by a spectrometer unit comprising a collimator (f ¼ 100 mm), a transmission grating (1200 lines∕mm), an achromatic doublet (f ¼ 200 mm), and a high-speed line scan camera (Basler sprint) operating at 70 kHz line rate using 2048 pixels per spectrum corresponding to a frame rate of ∼68 B-scans per second. A real-time display providing B-scan images at 28 frames per second and a continuously updating OCT z-projection image enabled speedy alignment of the mouse eye with respect to the beam. Data sets containing 1024 ðxÞ × 200 ðyÞ × 2048 ðkÞ pixels per polarization channel covering up to 3.5 mm ðxÞ × 3.5 mm ðyÞ × 2.7 mm (z, optical distance) were acquired in ∼3 s. ",
